{"title_page": "Sherman Howard", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sherman Howard\n| image        = Mr. Sherman Howard.jpg \n| image_size   = \n| caption      = Howard in 2014\n| birth_name   = Howard Lee Sherman\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1949|6|11}}\n| birth_place  = [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation   = Actor, voice actor\n| years_active = 1971\u2013present\n| education    = [[American Conservatory Theater]] (1971) \n| awards       =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Donna Bullock|1988}}\n| children     = 1\n| website      =\n}}\n'''Sherman Howard''' (born '''Howard Lee Sherman''' on June 11, 1949 in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]) is an American actor and voice actor, best known for his performance as the zombie Bub in [[George A. Romero]]'s ''[[Day of the Dead (1985 film)|Day of the Dead]]'' (1985).\n\n==Theatre==\nHoward began his career at the [[American Conservatory Theater]] in [[San Francisco]] in 1971. While a member of ACT's repertory company, he appeared in the roles of Glendenning in [[David Storey]]'s ''The Contractor'', The Archangel [[Gabriel]] in Nagle Jackson's ''The Mystery Cycle'', James in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Collection (play)|The Collection]]'', and Gratiano in ''[[The Merchant of Venice]]'', along with roles in both ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'' and ''[[Caesar and Cleopatra (play)|Caesar and Cleopatra]]''. He appeared as Archie in [[Tom Stoppard]]'s ''[[Jumpers (play)|Jumpers]]'' in the premiere season of Chicago's Northlight Theatre Company.\n\nWhile a member of the resident company at the [[Actors Theatre of Louisville]] for three seasons during the mid-70s, he played the role of Lucius in [[Jon Jory]]'s ''Andronicus: A Space Musical'', and had roles in ''[[The Runner Stumbles]]'', ''[[The Front Page]]'', ''[[The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui]]'', and the European tour of [[Marsha Norman]]'s ''[[Getting Out]]''. His [[off-Broadway]] credits include [[Shel Silverstein]]'s ''The Crate'' and ''The Lady or the Tiger Show'' as well as [[Sam Shepard]]'s ''[[Geography of a Horse Dreamer]]'' at the [[Ensemble Studio Theatre]], along with ''[[I'm Not Rappaport]]'' at the [[Roundabout Theatre Company]]. He appeared in ''[[Titus Andronicus]]'' and ''Tell Out My Soul'' at [[The Public Theater]], and in [[Lillian Hellman]]'s ''[[Another Part of the Forest]]'' at the Pecadillo Theatre. He most recently appeared in the title role of \"Bauer\" by Lauren Gunderson at 59 E 59th St in New York City.\n\nHis regional credits include Prospero in ''[[The Tempest]]'', King Henry in ''[[The Lion in Winter]]'', Spooner in ''[[No Man's Land (play)|No Man's Land]]'', and Lopakhin in ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]'' at the [[Shakespeare Theatre of New Jersey]] (STNJ), where he has also appeared in the title roles of both [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s ''[[Life of Galileo]]'' and [[Luigi Pirandello]]'s ''[[Henry IV (Pirandello)|Henry IV]]'' (Enrico IV). He also appeared as Scrooge in the STNJ's production of ''[[A Christmas Carol]]''. He played the role of Benedick in ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'', opposite his wife, Donna Bullock, as Beatrice. He played the title roles in both ''[[Hamlet]]'' and ''[[Macbeth]]'' at the [[Kentucky Shakespeare Festival]] and the North Carolina Shakespeare Festival, respectively. He appeared in the title role of ''Sheridan'' at the [[La Jolla Playhouse]]. He appeared in ''[[The Price (play)|The Price]]'' at the [[Pittsburgh Public Theater]] and in ''Nine Armenians'' at the Intiman Theater in [[Seattle]]. His [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include ''[[Bengal Tiger at the Baghdad Zoo]]'', ''[[All My Sons]]'', ''[[Inherit the Wind (play)|Inherit the Wind]]'', and [[Gore Vidal]]'s ''[[The Best Man (play)|The Best Man]]''. He recently concluded a run at the [[Old Globe Theatre]] in [[San Diego]] as The Player in Tom Stoppard's ''[[Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead]]'' and appeared in \"The Second Mrs. Wilson\" at George Street Playhouse under the direction of Gordon Edelstein.\n\nHoward also has a passion for concert hall music. In their 2013/14, season he performed with the Philadelphia Orchestra in Rachmaninoff's \"The Bells\" conducted by Vladimir Jurowski. He also appeared in the role of Prospero in the New Jersey Symphony Orchestra's presentation of Jean Sibelius' ''The Tempest Suite'' conducted by Jacque Lacombe. He has performed Richard Strauss's \"Enoch Arden\" with concert pianist, David Kaplan at Bargemusic in Brooklyn and Metropolis Ensemble in Manhattan.\n\n==Personal life==\nHoward has been married to actress [[Donna Bullock (actress)|Donna Bullock]] since May 1988. They have one child, Hannah Sherman.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/24/Sherman-Howard.html Sherman Howard Biography (1949-)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"white-space:nowrap\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|1984||''[[Grace Quigley]]''|| Alan ||Credited as '''Howard Sherman'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985||''The Eagle and the Bear''||  ||TV Movie <br/> Credited as '''Howard Sherman'''\n|-\n|''[[Day of the Dead (1985 film)|Day of the Dead]]''|| Bub ||Credited as '''Howard Sherman'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 |1988||''Necessity''|| Jack Martinelli ||TV Movie\n|-\n|''[[The House on Carroll Street]]''|| Boria ||Credited as ''''Howard Sherman'''\n|-\n|rowspan=4 |1989||''[[Casualties of War]]''|| Court Martial President ||\n|-\n|''[[Lethal Weapon 2]]''|| Hitman #3 ||\n|-\n|''[[K-9 (film)|K-9]]''|| Dillon ||\n|-\n|''[[Three Fugitives]]''|| Canadian Police Officer ||Uncredited\n|-\n|1990||''[[Dark Angel (1990 film)|Dark Angel]]''|| Victor Manning ||\n|-\n|1991||''[[Ricochet_(film)|Ricochet]]''|| Kiley ||\n|-\n|1993||''The Hit List''|| Bishop ||\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1995||''[[Tom Clancy's Op Center (film)|Tom Clancy's Op Center]]''|| Uri Stalipin ||TV Movie\n|-\n|''[[Problem Ch